  <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Now, return to the <fr:link href="/lectures/002Z/" title="Some more example logics" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/002Z/" display-uri="002Z" type="local">five example logics above</fr:link>.
    Which of these, if any, are stronger or weaker than which of these?
    Take a moment to think this through before you go on.
</html:p>

	
	
	
	<fr:tree show-metadata="false" expanded="false" toc="false" numbered="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>2</fr:month><fr:day>20</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>Solution</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
<html:ul><html:li>Logic 1 is weaker than logic 2, which is to say that 2 is stronger than 1.</html:li>
<html:li>Logic 1 is weaker than logic 4, which is to say that 4 is stronger than 1.</html:li>
<html:li>Each of logics 1--5, like any logic, is both stronger and weaker than itself.</html:li>
<html:li>There are no other relations of strength among these examples.</html:li></html:ul>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter>
