            <fr:title text="Stronger and weaker">Stronger and weaker</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>     There's some vocabulary that often gets used to talk about relationships between logics: we can say that some logic is <html:strong>stronger</html:strong> or <html:strong>weaker</html:strong> than another.</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
                <fr:authors>
                  <fr:author>
                    <fr:link href="/lectures/ellieripley/" title="Ellie Ripley" uri="https://negation.rocks/lectures/ellieripley/" display-uri="ellieripley" type="local">Ellie Ripley</fr:link>
                  </fr:author>
                </fr:authors>
                <fr:date>
                  <fr:year>2026</fr:year>
                  <fr:month>2</fr:month>
                  <fr:day>17</fr:day>
                </fr:date>
                <fr:uri>https://negation.rocks/lectures/0031/</fr:uri>
                <fr:display-uri>0031</fr:display-uri>
                <fr:route>/lectures/0031/</fr:route>
                <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>To say that a logic X is <html:strong>stronger</html:strong> than a logic Y means exactly the same as to say that Y is <html:strong>weaker</html:strong> than X, and they both mean exactly this: that Y is a <html:em>subset</html:em> of X.</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>    This isn't a new idea; it's just a couple of new words that we use for the idea of one logic's being a subset of another.
    So, for example the empty logic is weaker than every logic, and the universal logic is stronger than every logic; that's just a way of saying what you already know about these logics and the subset relation.
</html:p>
            <html:p>     Note that there's a potentially confusing feature here: saying that logic X is stronger than logic Y does <html:em>not</html:em> mean that X and Y are different logics!
    Indeed, every logic is both stronger and weaker than itself, since every set is a subset of itself.
    Again, there's nothing <html:em>conceptually</html:em> new here, but the phrasing can be confusing at first; make sure to be careful!
</html:p>
            <html:p>     Note, too, that the only way for a logic X to be both stronger and weaker than a logic Y is for X and Y to be the very same logic (by extensionality).
    But it is common, given two different logics, for neither of them to be stronger or weaker than the other.
    All it takes is for each of them to contain some argument that the other does not.
</html:p>
