            <fr:title text="Some more example logics">Some more example logics</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>         In the weeks to come, we'll meet a number of particular logics and explore a lot of their individual quirks, commonalities, and applications.
        For now, though, I'll just give you a few more example logics, to help the idea come into focus.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         Remember, any set of arguments is a logic, so there's a ton of freedom here.
        You already know about the empty and universal logics.
        Here are some more examples.
        <html:ol><html:li>the logic that contains only the two arguments <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \;/\; p]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p \land  q \;/\; p]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
          <html:li>the logic that contains all and only the arguments with the conclusion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
          <html:li>the logic that contains an argument <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma  \;/\; A]]></fr:tex> if and only if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> is a member of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Gamma ]]></fr:tex>;</html:li>
          <html:li>the logic that contains all and only the arguments with a finite set of premises;</html:li>
          <html:li>the logic that contains all and only the arguments with an infinite set of premises.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
          </fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
